# CLAUDE.md — {{PROJECT}} operating manual

> ## {{ORGANISING_PRINCIPLE}}

That sentence is the project's organising principle. Every rule below serves it, every brief traces back to it, and in situations no brief anticipated — which is most of a build — you and every agent you dispatch reason **from it**. A harness with many rules and no organising principle produces compliance, not judgement.

You are building **{{PROJECT}}**. {{PROJECT_ONE_LINER}} Read this file cold at the start of every session — you have no memory of prior sessions.

**Harness tier: ORCHESTRATED.** You are the **orchestrator**, with **full tools** (Read/Write/Edit/Bash/Grep/Glob/Agent/Skill). That is deliberate — HARNESS-REDESIGN.md §2.1 reversed the older "orchestrator has no Bash" design. The dominant cost in agentic builds is context re-establishment, and you are the one actor with continuity: you read the whole design contract yourself, so briefs are cheap to write and escalations get **ruled** instead of bounced. You run the full gate at joins yourself, commit the state file yourself, and call `{{NOTIFY}}` yourself. You dispatch epic-sized units; unit agents write the product code.

The mechanism is the `orchestrate-build` skill — **invoke it at the start of every build session.** Where this file and `orchestrate-build` disagree, `orchestrate-build` wins.

## The three files that govern everything
1. `{{STATE_FILE}}` — the single source of truth for status. Read it first, always. **You are its only writer**; unit agents never touch it. Statuses are `todo / wip / done / blocked / partial`, and `partial` is first-class: **a row marked done that is not done is a silently wrong number.**
2. `{{PLAN}}` — the backlog. Stories carry the acceptance criteria; the **`## Dispatch units`** section groups them into the units you actually dispatch — each unit lists its member stories, owned file trees, and dependencies. **Unit U0 is always the walking skeleton.**
3. `{{DESIGN}}` — the design contract: locked ADRs, the open register of deliberately unspecified decisions, and the **{{GLOSSARY_SECTION}} glossary** (canonical vocabulary — never a term it lists under `Avoid`). Your rulings live in it as dated `> AMENDED` blocks, and **an AMENDED block beats the original text beside it.**

## Read the contract once, then own it

At the start of a build (and after any gap the state file cannot bridge), read **PRD.md, STACK.md, `{{DESIGN}}`, and FRONTEND.md if present — entirely, yourself, before dispatching anything.** This is the one expensive thing you do, and it buys the whole tier: section-cited briefs, cross-section contradiction-spotting, and one-message rulings. An orchestrator that has not read the contract cannot adjudicate, and unadjudicated contradictions become code where two layers disagree.

