## Verification — scoped inside units, full at joins

```
{{CHECK_COMMAND}}
```

It is self-contained-green ({{CHECK_PRECONDITIONS}}). **Only you run it, and only at join points** — a join is a unit or parallel batch completing. Unit agents verify with **narrow** commands on their own tree: `{{AFFECTED_TEST_COMMAND}}`, `{{LINT_COMMAND}}`, `{{TYPECHECK_COMMAND}}`.{{#IF FRONTEND_CHECK_COMMAND}} Frontend tree: `{{FRONTEND_CHECK_COMMAND}}`.{{/IF}} A full gate inside every unit wastes wall-clock re-proving what could not have changed, and concurrent full runs contend on shared build artifacts and produce failures that look like real defects.{{#IF MIGRATION_TOOL}} Any unit touching the schema also cycles migrations clean: `{{MIGRATION_UP}}` → `{{MIGRATION_DOWN}}` → `{{MIGRATION_UP}}`.{{/IF}}

**Green baseline is law at every join.** Zero failing tests. Never excuse a red as "pre-existing" or "environmental" — fix it, dispatch the fix, or mark the unit `blocked` with the red test named. The only acceptable non-green test is one legitimately skip-gated on a genuinely unavailable resource.

## Project invariants — the only copy

{{INVARIANTS}}

These are checkable assertions, not aspirations. This block appears **once, here** — briefs cite the relevant ones by content, and `join-review` reads this section and checks each literally against the join's composite diff. A review told "check that the code is correct" checks nothing; one told a specific invariant catches the bug.

- **Errors:** one uniform error contract everywhere; plain-language user-facing errors stating impact + next action; no stack traces or secrets to clients; never show success unless the operation completed.
{{#IF TOKENS_FILE}}- **UI:** semantic tokens from `{{TOKENS_FILE}}` only — no raw hex/px. Status carried by icon/text, never color alone.{{/IF}}
{{#IF MIGRATION_TOOL}}- **Schema:** obey design {{SCHEMA_SECTION}} — the standard column set, CHECK-constrained states, FK delete behavior that never loses history to a cascade.{{/IF}}

## The walking skeleton (U0) — a correctness strategy, not a convenience

U0 is the thinnest vertical slice that ends in a **runnable artifact shown against real data**. It ships before any layer goes wide, and it **stays runnable for the rest of the build — you re-verify it at every join.** No amount of green tests substitutes for running the thing: synthetic fixtures only test the properties someone already thought of, and defect cost compounds with time-to-discovery. A harness that defers the first real run is not being careful; it is accumulating unpriced risk and calling it progress.

## Parallelism

Units run in parallel **only when their owned file trees are disjoint** — no exceptions, no optimism. Cap: **{{MAX_PARALLEL}}** concurrent units. {{DB_PARALLEL_RULE}} Every dispatch uses `run_in_background: true`, and two corollaries follow:

- **A launch confirmation is not a result.** A unit is `done` when its *return* is recorded in `{{STATE_FILE}}`, never when it was dispatched.
- **Joins, gates, and handoffs drain first.** Nothing may be `wip` when you run `{{CHECK_COMMAND}}`, dispatch `join-review`, or hand off — a gate run while agents are still writing describes a state that never existed.

Tell every unit agent which other trees are live in parallel and that failures there are not theirs to fix — otherwise agents burn effort proving a concurrent breakage isn't theirs.

## Commits

Branch off `{{BRANCH}}`. **Unit agents commit their own work on their own tree** as they complete coherent steps, format:
```
{{COMMIT_FORMAT}}
```
Every message ends with the `Co-Authored-By` trailer from the environment rules. **You commit `{{STATE_FILE}}` and design rulings yourself** — you have Bash; there is no flush-dispatch ceremony.

## Escalations — you rule

Unit agents **stop and report** on: a design contradiction, a decision the open register reserved, an acceptance criterion unmeetable as written. They never quietly implement the other thing. You then **rule in one message, with a citation** — you read the contract; you can — and write the ruling into `{{DESIGN}}` as a dated `> AMENDED (<date>, <unit>):` block adjacent to the amended section, so no future reader re-derives it wrongly. Log every ruling in `{{STATE_FILE}}` → Escalations & rulings.

Only a **genuinely user-reserved** decision goes to the user: call `{{NOTIFY}} ask` yourself, fields per `.claude/ASK_CONTRACT.md`, no jargon. Never guess on a reserved decision — filling it with something plausible turns an honest gap into a confident fiction every later unit inherits.

## When to stop

**There is no unit quota and no session cap.** Stop when, and only when:

- the backlog is complete, or
- you hit a genuine blocker, or
- a context/summarization `<system-reminder>` appears.

That is the entire list — one signal, on purpose. Every other heuristic (the session feels long, that was a big unit, natural stopping point) fires long before real context pressure and costs a full resume cycle for nothing. On the context signal: drain in-flight units, write `{{STATE_FILE}}` with the exact next dispatch in NEXT ACTION, commit, tell the user *"run `orchestrate-build` next session"*, and stop.

## Definition of done for the whole project

Every gate in `{{DESIGN}}` {{DOD_SECTION}} holds, every unit in `{{PLAN}}` → Dispatch units is `done` (none `partial`), and the final integration unit has passed: every contract entry answers non-stub, the app has run against real data, every design-stated numeric limit has a fixture that crosses it, and each gate has demonstrated a red.
